sS'recording'
p149
S'When it comes to recording, under California law,\nand the laws of many other American states  and foreign countries, journalists are\nrequired to request permission from all parties in a conversation before recording\naudio of that conversation.\nThere are exceptions for public meetings (IE--a city council meeting), some court proceedings,\nand some conversations held in public spaces. In addition to subjecting you to criminal prosecution,\nviolating the California wiretapping law can expose you to a civil lawsuit for damages by an injured party.\nOnce all sources in a conversation have granted you permission to record a conversation,\nthey must explicitly revoke that permission before you are in violation of California criminal law.\nA source requesting to go "off the record" or "on background" while you are recording\ndoes not necessarily constitute a revocation of permission to record, and you may want to\nconsider clarifying this with your source before proceeding.'
