sS'on the record'
p439
S'A source is considered on the record once you have identified yourself as a journalist.\nPacific Standard recommends keeping sources on the record whenever possible,\nand recommends against relying on confusing terms like \xe2\x80\x9coff the record,\xe2\x80\x9d \xe2\x80\x9con background,\xe2\x80\x9d\n\xe2\x80\x9con deep background,\xe2\x80\x9d or \xe2\x80\x9cnot for attribution\xe2\x80\x9d in negotiating  terms of engagement with sources.\nMost outlets and journalists subscribe to their own definitions for these terms, and the public\nhas little to no familiarity with them.\nIf a source requests a status other than \xe2\x80\x9con the record," negotiate specifically\nabout what information you are willing to print but not attribute to the source by name;\nwhat kind of anonymizing attribution you and the source are comfortable with;\nand what information you are willing to leave out of a story, or or willing to try\nto confirm with other sources later. Note that these are ethical, not legal, considerations.\nPacific Standard expects its reporters to be open, honest, and consistent with sources--especially\nthose that have less experience dealing with media or are otherwise vulnerable--and to adhere\nto negotiated terms of engagement.'
